"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910343","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-04","<p>The regulations made under the Housing and Planning Act 2016 introduced banning orders for private landlords and property agents who have been convicted of serious housing, immigration and other criminal offences. The regulations came into force on 6 April 2018 and apply to England only.</p><p>A relevant offence must have been committed on or after 6 April 2018 for a local housing authority to be permitted to apply for a banning order. A notice of intent must be made by the local authority within 6 months of the landlord being convicted of the offence followed by an application to the First Tier Tribunal which has the power to issue the banning order.</p><p>To date no banning orders have been made by the First Tier Tribunal.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-06-04T11:30:30.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910343/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910343/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Landlords","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many banning orders for landlords were (a) issued and (b) accepted in each nation and region of the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","147360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910344","Home Office","false","2018-07-06","<p>The response for UIN 136368 was answered on 03 July 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-06T10:45:58.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910344/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910344/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Home Office: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when he plans to answer Question 136368, tabled on 18 April 2018 by the hon. Member for Brighton Pavilion.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","147427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910345","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-08","<p>The Pharmacy Integration Fund (PhIF) programme of work started in 2016/17. From the PHIF, funding for schemes to support pharmacists working in general practitioner surgeries was £0 in 2016/17 with £5 million allocated in both 2017/18 and 2018/19. In 2016/17, £210,000 was allocated to schemes to support community pharmacies to become better integrated with the National Health Service, with a further estimated spend of £2,140,000 in 2017/18 and £2.5 million allocated for 2018/19. These figures do not however include funding for a wide range of Health Education England training schemes, including for community pharmacy staff which is additional.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016/17, £1,784,000 and an estimated £21,799,630 in 2017/18 was appropriated from the PhIF to support other parts of the NHS.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-08T10:46:10.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910345/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910345/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Pharmacy Integration Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what funds have been appropriated from the Pharmacy Integration Fund, in each year on (a) schemes to support pharmacists working in GP surgeries, (b) schemes to support community pharmacies to become better integrated with the NHS and (c) deferring the cost of (i) other parts of the NHS and (ii) wider Government expenditure.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","147482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910346","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-08","<p>The Department has made no specific assessment on the financial impact of appointing a data protection officer on independent community pharmacies or other primary healthcare providers.</p><p> </p><p>It is the responsibility of each organisation to ensure their compliance with the General Data Protection Regulation which came into effect on 25 May 2018. For the past year we have been working alongside system partners across health and social care in developing a comprehensive suite of guidance products to help organisations recognise their obligations and help put effective governance and risk management arrangements in place from 25 May. These guidance materials are available to all health and care organisations on the NHS Digital website and will include guidance to general practice, optometry, pharmaceutical and dental organisations. In addition, there is considerable information and guidance available from the Information Commissioner’s Office.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-06-08T11:03:39.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910346/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910346/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Pharmacy and Primary Health Care: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made on the financial effect of appointing a data protection officer on (a) independent community pharmacies and (b) other primary healthcare providers.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","147483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910347","Cabinet Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Chancellor of Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for Cabinet Office and I met with Professor Chris Whitty, the then Acting Government Chief Scientific Adviser and Rupert Lewis, Director of Government Office for Science on 28 Feb 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Cabinet Office officials and Ministers regularly meet with government scientific advisers.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-06-06T14:19:48.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910347/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910347/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-23","Cabinet Office: Government Chief Scientific Adviser","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many meetings he had with the Government’s Chief Scientific Adviser between 1 January and 31 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","147375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910348","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Chief Scientific Adviser attended meetings with the Secretary of State for Justice on two occasions between 1 January and 31 March 2018.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-06-04T13:41:44.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910348/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910348/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-23","Ministry of Justice: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many meetings he had with his Department's Chief Scientific Adviser between 1 January and 31 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","147376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910349","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-08","<p>Spend on the Pharmacy Integration Fund was £216,305 in 2016/17 and is estimated to be £18,200,370 in 2017/18. A further £40 million has been committed for 2018/19.</p><p> </p><p>Delays to planned expenditure did result in an underspend against the funding allocated to this programme. As is standard Government finance procedure, underspends cannot be carried forward by either NHS England or the Department. As a result some of this funding was appropriated to support other programmes outside of pharmacy. The Government however remains committed to this programme which is already having a real impact and which will continue to develop.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-08T11:02:28.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910349/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910349/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Pharmacy Integration Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health of 20 December 2016, Official Report, how much of the £300 million pharmacy integration fund has been expended.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","147484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910350","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-07","<p>The Pharmacy Integration Fund (PhIF) has been used to support the employment of pharmacists in integrated urgent care, general practice and care homes where their expert knowledge is helping to optimise the use of medicines and improve clinical effectiveness to deliver better outcomes for patients, including in respect to repeat prescriptions. They receive additional training enabling them to prescribe and have access to the full clinical record meaning they are well placed to support patients with complex polypharmacy and multiple co-morbidities. Alongside this, the NHS Urgent Medicines Supply Advanced Service has made it easier and faster for patients to access medication that they have previously been prescribed.</p><p> </p><p>To further support and promote the use of pharmacies by patients with minor ailments, the Digital Minor Illness Referral Service is piloting new urgent care pathways to direct patients into community pharmacy from NHS 111 Online and the NHS 111 phone line. In parallel, Government continues to promote pharmacy as the first port of call for a wide range of minor health concerns through the “Stay Well Pharmacy” campaign.</p><p> </p><p>Underpinning these work streams the PhIF is also funding training and leadership programmes which are also expected to drive improvements across these areas.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-07T16:11:02.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910350/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910350/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Pharmacy Integration Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health of 20 December 2016, Official Report, what projects have been funded through the pharmacy integration fund to support improvements in (a) repeat prescriptions and (b) minor ailment services in England.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","147485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910351","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-06-04","<p>There have been no meetings with the Chief Scientific Adviser and the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland between 1 January and 31 March 2018.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-06-04T14:26:29.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910351/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910351/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-23","Northern Ireland Office: Government Chief Scientific Adviser","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many meetings she had with the Government’s Chief Scientific Adviser between 1 January and 31 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","147377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910352","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-06-11","<p>Between 1 January and 31 March 2018 the Secretary of State met Chris Jones, Chief Scientific Adviser at DExEU, four times. It should be noted that this is a dual role combined with his position as the Director of Justice, Security and Migration.</p><p> </p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-06-11T15:57:14.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910352/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910352/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-23","Department for Exiting the European Union: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many meetings he had with his Department’s Chief Scientific Adviser between 1 January and 31 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","147378"
