"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910374","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>Local authorities are responsible for defining and procuring 30 hours systems that best fit their needs and requirements. As these requirements vary across local authorities, the department does not provide scrutiny of these systems.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-04T06:32:11.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910374/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910374/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the answer of 23 May to Question 143823 on Children: Day Care, what scrutiny his Department undertakes on the effectiveness of IT systems procured by local authorities to support the 30 free hours of childcare policy.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","147498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910375","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Department does not hold this data. We understand that many landlords ask for rent in advance and it is part of the agreement between individual tenant and landlord. As responsible companies with a social purpose we expect housing associations to let their homes in a fair, transparent and efficient way that takes into account the housing needs of tenants and potential tenants.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-06-04T11:29:47.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910375/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910375/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Housing Associations: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has made an estimate of the number of housing associations which request upfront payment of rent in advance before an offered tenancy can be secured.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","147503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910376","Department for Education","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Department has been considering the evidence gathered during the recent call for evidence and wider engagement exercise to help shape the new subjects of Relationships Education and Relationships and Sex Education, and draft new guidance and regulations.</p><p> </p><p>The Department plans to consult on these draft regulations and the guidance shortly before laying the regulations to allow a debate in both Houses. The Department will continue to work towards schools being able to teach these subjects from September 2019.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-06-05T15:18:33.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910376/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910376/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Sex and Relationship Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department plans to meet the deadline of September 2019 for the introduction of compulsory relationships and sex education lessons in secondary schools; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","147511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910377","Home Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>In line with the Government’s longstanding policy, I can neither confirm nor deny whether Mr Hall is the subject of an INTERPOL notice or diffusion. The National Crime Agency hosts the UK National Crime Bureau which is responsible for handling INTERPOL requests in the UK. It is operationally independent from the Home Office, it would not be appropriate for me to pursue such issues directly with the NCA or INTERPOL.</p><p>However, I can assure you that any misuse of INTERPOL notices is taken very seriously by the government. The then Home Secretary raised this issue with INTERPOL Secretary General Stock on 18 April, and the UK has taken a strongly supportive stance in relation to INTERPOL’s efforts to ensure robust systems are in place to protect human rights and preclude interventions or activities of a political, military, religious or racial character.</p><p>I note that any person who is the subject of information processed in the INTERPOL information system may submit a request directly to INTERPOL’s Commission for the Control of INTERPOL’s Files (CCF), an independent body which ensures processing of personal information by INTERPOL complies with its regulations for access to, correction or deletion of data relating to them.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","147397","2018-06-07T15:35:44.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910377/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910377/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Andy Hall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether his Department has (a) made a submission to and (b) had other forms of engagement with Interpol on the potential issuance of a red or diffusion notice by the Interpol National Central Bureau of Thailand in relation to Mr Andy Hall’s human rights work in Thailand.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","147396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910378","Home Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>In line with the Government’s longstanding policy, I can neither confirm nor deny whether Mr Hall is the subject of an INTERPOL notice or diffusion. The National Crime Agency hosts the UK National Crime Bureau which is responsible for handling INTERPOL requests in the UK. It is operationally independent from the Home Office, it would not be appropriate for me to pursue such issues directly with the NCA or INTERPOL.</p><p>However, I can assure you that any misuse of INTERPOL notices is taken very seriously by the government. The then Home Secretary raised this issue with INTERPOL Secretary General Stock on 18 April, and the UK has taken a strongly supportive stance in relation to INTERPOL’s efforts to ensure robust systems are in place to protect human rights and preclude interventions or activities of a political, military, religious or racial character.</p><p>I note that any person who is the subject of information processed in the INTERPOL information system may submit a request directly to INTERPOL’s Commission for the Control of INTERPOL’s Files (CCF), an independent body which ensures processing of personal information by INTERPOL complies with its regulations for access to, correction or deletion of data relating to them.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","147396","2018-06-07T15:35:44.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910378/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910378/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Andy Hall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what support his Department is providing under the UN Guiding Principles On Business and Human Rights to human rights defender Mr Andy Hall on a potential red or diffusion notice being issued by Interpol.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","147397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910379","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>Local authorities are responsible for improving the health of their local population and reducing health inequalities by assessing local need and commissioning services to meet identified needs, including drug dependence.</p><p> </p><p>In the current financial year, local authorities are receiving a £3.215 billion public health grant for their public health duties for all ages. Information about the 2018-19 grant, how it breaks down and indicative public health allocations for each local authority in 2019-20 is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/public-health-grants-to-local-authorities-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/public-health-grants-to-local-authorities-2018-to-2019</a></p><p> </p><p>Public Health England supports local authorities in their work of needs assessment and commissioning of alcohol and drug prevention and treatment services by providing advice, guidance and data.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-04T13:53:19.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910379/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910379/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Drugs: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department is taking steps to ensure that recovery services for drug addiction in Barnsley are receiving sufficient funding.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","147445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910380","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 provides the police and local authorities with a range of flexible powers that they can use to tackle anti-social behaviour. It is a matter for the relevant agencies in Barnsley, as in other areas, to decide when it is appropriate to make use of these powers.</p><p>The Home Office published refreshed statutory guidance for frontline professionals on the use of the statutory powers in December 2017. The guidance is available to the police and local authorities and it will assist them in addressing anti-social behaviour.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-05T14:07:33.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910380/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910380/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Antisocial Behaviour: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps his Department is taking to tackle anti-social behaviour in Barnsley.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","147446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910381","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>Local authorities must ensure there are sufficient good school places for all pupils, including those with special educational needs and disabilities. If a local authority identifies a shortage of special school places for children and young people in its area, resulting in a significant number having to travel a long way to access an appropriate placement, it will need to consider creating or expanding specialist provision, either attached to mainstream schools or in special schools.</p><p>The department has allocated £215 million of capital funding (over and above basic need funding) to help build new places at mainstream and special schools, and to improve existing places to benefit current and future pupils. Local authorities, through consultation with local stakeholders, should decide how best to spend their allocation to meet local needs.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-04T06:16:55.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910381/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910381/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Autism: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will take steps to ensure that people in Barnsley with severe autism have local access to specialist schools and services without having to travel to Wakefield or Rotherham for such school and services.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","147447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910382","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>We recognise the challenges that special schools face supporting pupils with high levels of need, that is why base funding is set at a much higher level of £10,000 per place. On top of this, local authorities provide top up funding to reflect additional need in respect of individual pupils. The level of the top-up funding is a matter for agreement between the local authority and the school, and we do not prescribe in detail how local authorities should allocate their high needs funding.</p><p> </p><p>To assist local authorities in making sure that special schools have sufficient resources, in 2018-19 we have provided Barnsley with £21.9 million in high needs funding, 3.1% more than they planned to spend in 2017-18. These allocations can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-04T06:20:41.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910382/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910382/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Autism: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department is taking steps to ensure that specialist schools in Barnsley have sufficient resources to teach people who have severe autism.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","147448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910383","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-04","<p>Universal Credit already captures information on claimants with complex needs, including care leavers, as part of the claimant profile.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-04T13:54:21.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910383/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910383/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-23","Universal Credit: Care Leavers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether she plans to flag care leavers in the universal credit system as currently with job seekers allowance.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","147302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910384","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>The number of children entering the care system in the last 10 years is provided in the attached table.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-04T10:13:15.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910384/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910384/answer","147303_children_entering_care_system_in_the_last_10_years.pdf","147303_children_entering_care_system_in_the_last_10_years.pdf","147303_children_entering_care_system_last_10_years","147303_children_entering_care_system_last_10_years","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910384/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children were taken into care in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","147303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910385","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>From 18 April 2016 to 1 May 2018, 426 academy orders have been issued to inadequate local authority maintained schools. Of the 218 schools that have opened as sponsored academies none have been inspected as an academy to date.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted will usually inspect new schools, including academies when they are in their third year of operation. Ofsted may conduct an inspection of any new school at any time, including within three years of opening, where information held or received causes sufficient concern.</p><p> </p><p>Of the remaining 208 schools that have not opened as a sponsored academy, 39 have been re-inspected, 37 of which have seen their Ofsted grade improve. 186 of the 208 schools are in the process of becoming sponsored academies, 77 of which received an academy order within the last 9 months. 21 schools from the 208 have had their academy orders revoked and are no longer progressing towards conversion. The department supports all schools becoming sponsored academies to have school improvement plans in place regardless of their place in the process.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-04T07:44:57.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910385/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910385/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Academies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the answer to Question 145610 of 23 May 2018 on Academies, how many of the schools that (a) opened as sponsored academies and (b) did not open as sponsored academies have received a new Ofsted grade better than inadequate since directive academy orders were issued.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","147466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910386","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>The recruitment process for the Social Mobility Commissioners will begin in the coming weeks. This process will not be completed until a new Chair is formally appointed. This will allow the Chair to be involved in the process of recruiting a high quality Board with a range of skills and expertise.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-04T06:08:33.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910386/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910386/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Social Mobility Commission: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to his Department's press release entitled New Chair of the Social Mobility Commission recommended, published by his Department on 23 May 2018, what the timetable is for the appointment process for the remaining Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commissioners to commence.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","147467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910387","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-04","<p>In January 2017, Southern launched the on-board supervisor on routes where the technology allows the driver to control the doors. The conductors on these services were moved to an on-board supervisor (OBS) role. Since then approximately 1.3% of these services have operated without their rostered on-board supervisor for the full journey. This only happens in certain exceptional circumstances such as staff sickness or the second staff member running late.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-06-04T16:01:03.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910387/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910387/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-23","Southern","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of Southern trains have operated without an onboard supervisor in each month since guards were discontinued.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","147296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910388","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-07","<p>The majority of airfields in the UK are privately run and owned. Like other business enterprises, potential investors and owners of new aerodromes can benefit from a range of measures that the Government has set in place to support businesses and promote growth, as well as support from regional and local government. Information on the amount of historic public investment in aerodromes is not held centrally.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","147289","2018-06-07T14:04:43.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910388/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910388/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-23","Aviation: Facilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the amount of historic public investment in aerodromes in years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","147288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910389","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-07","<p>The majority of airfields in the UK are privately run and owned. Like other business enterprises, potential investors and owners of new aerodromes can benefit from a range of measures that the Government has set in place to support businesses and promote growth, as well as support from regional and local government. Information on the amount of historic public investment in aerodromes is not held centrally.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","147288","2018-06-07T14:04:43.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910389/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910389/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-23","Aviation: Facilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what support his Department plans to make available for the provision of new aerodromes.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","147289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910390","Treasury","false","2018-06-08","<p>For the years 2012-13 to 2016-17 inclusive, around £8m per year was raised from fuel duty on aviation fuel for pleasure flying. There is no duty on aviation fuel used by commercial jets.</p><p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-06-08T09:32:27.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910390/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910390/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Aviation: Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much revenue was raised from fuel duty on aviation fuel in the last five years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","147290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910391","Treasury","false","2018-06-06","<p>UK law allows an exemption from VAT for vocational training. This exemption is available to all EU Member States under the EU VAT framework.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-06-06T14:51:01.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910391/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910391/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Aviation: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what comparisons he has made of the taxation of flight training in the UK with such taxation in other countries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","147291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910392","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-04","<p>There are six Enterprise Zones in England that include active public aerodromes: Aerohub+ (Newquay Airport); Blackpool Airport; Heart of the South West (Exeter Airport); Luton Airport; North Kent (Rochester Airport); and Solent (Solent Airport).</p><p> </p><p>There are a further three Enterprise Zones in England with large sites in close proximity to an active public aerodrome but not within its’ operational boundary. This includes: Humber (Humberside Airport); Manchester Airport (Manchester Airport) and North East Round 2 (Newcastle Airport). The Lancashire Enterprise Zone also includes sites within the boundaries of the privately operated Warton aerodrome.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-04T16:03:35.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910392/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910392/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-23","Aviation: Enterprise Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which aerodromes are located within the Enterprise Zones.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","147292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910393","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","The Government remains committed to ending six figure pay outs in the public sector. The regulations to implement the exit payment cap were drafted as part of the passage of the Enterprise Act 2016. Since that time, they have undergone further iteration and will be completed following the outcome of the consultation and then laid in Parliament. It is not possible to forecast the hours required to reflect the degree of changes which may be made to the draft regulations following the outcome of the consultation, which will necessarily depend on consultees views and the Government’s response to that consultation. The consultation will seek views on the terms of the draft secondary legislation, including the detailed design of the exit payment cap and the list of bodies to which the cap will apply.","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","147305 ; 147308","2018-06-04T12:27:08.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910393/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910393/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2018 to Question 129888, on Public Sector: Redundancy Pay, when the process of drafting the necessary regulations began; when that drafting is forecast to be completed; and what the projected number of hours for that drafting process is.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","147304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910394","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","The Government remains committed to ending six figure pay outs in the public sector. The regulations to implement the exit payment cap were drafted as part of the passage of the Enterprise Act 2016. Since that time, they have undergone further iteration and will be completed following the outcome of the consultation and then laid in Parliament. It is not possible to forecast the hours required to reflect the degree of changes which may be made to the draft regulations following the outcome of the consultation, which will necessarily depend on consultees views and the Government’s response to that consultation. The consultation will seek views on the terms of the draft secondary legislation, including the detailed design of the exit payment cap and the list of bodies to which the cap will apply.","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","147304 ; 147308","2018-06-04T12:27:08.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910394/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910394/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 4 December 2017 to Question 116646, on Public Sector: Redundancy Pay, for what reasons a consultation was not brought forward in the first quarter of 2018.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","147305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910395","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","<p>Figures published in the Whole of Government Accounts show that during the period of April 2015 to March 2016 there were 1,787 exits paid at over £100,000, costing £0.2bn. There were 5,439 exit payments paid at between £50,000 and £100,000 costing £0.3bn, of which a portion may have been more than £95,000. The Whole of Government Accounts figures for the period since the Enterprise Act 2016 came into force, on May 4 2016, are not yet available and no separate estimate has been made.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","147307","2018-06-04T12:42:50.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910395/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910395/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of exit payments for public sector workers which have exceeded £95,000 since the Enterprise Act 2016 came into force.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","147306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910396","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","<p>Figures published in the Whole of Government Accounts show that during the period of April 2015 to March 2016 there were 1,787 exits paid at over £100,000, costing £0.2bn. There were 5,439 exit payments paid at between £50,000 and £100,000 costing £0.3bn, of which a portion may have been more than £95,000. The Whole of Government Accounts figures for the period since the Enterprise Act 2016 came into force, on May 4 2016, are not yet available and no separate estimate has been made.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","147306","2018-06-04T12:42:50.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910396/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910396/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of exit payments for public sector workers which have exceeded £95,000 since the Enterprise Act 2016 came into force.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","147307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910397","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","The Government remains committed to ending six figure pay outs in the public sector. The regulations to implement the exit payment cap were drafted as part of the passage of the Enterprise Act 2016. Since that time, they have undergone further iteration and will be completed following the outcome of the consultation and then laid in Parliament. It is not possible to forecast the hours required to reflect the degree of changes which may be made to the draft regulations following the outcome of the consultation, which will necessarily depend on consultees views and the Government’s response to that consultation. The consultation will seek views on the terms of the draft secondary legislation, including the detailed design of the exit payment cap and the list of bodies to which the cap will apply.","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","147304 ; 147305","2018-06-04T12:27:08.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910397/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910397/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 4 December 2017 to Question 116646, on Public Sector: Redundancy Pay, what the matters are for which it was planned a 12 week consultation would take place in the first quarter of 2018; and whether there has been any change in what those matters are since December 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","147308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910398","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>Through the Pupil Premium the Government continues to provide additional funding, nearly £2.5 billion this year, to help schools improve the progress and attainment of disadvantaged pupils; high proportions of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller pupils will benefit from this support.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2018 the Department established the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller stakeholder group to inform policy to raise the attainment of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller pupils. In March 2018, a review of exclusions was launched, led by Edward Timpson, who will be supported by an expert reference group providing expertise on the school system and perspectives of pupils more likely to be excluded. The group includes an advisor with extensive experience working with Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities. The Department continues to work with the Ministry for Housing, Communities and Local Government on their 2018/19 pilot programme to improve the social integration of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities. In addition, as part of the Careers Strategy, the Department will include Gypsy, Roma and Traveller youth as a target group for a pilot, testing ways of providing careers guidance to vulnerable groups.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-06-04T06:49:34.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910398/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910398/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Pupils: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to improve the attainment of pupils from (a) gypsy and roma and (b) Irish Traveller backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","147450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910399","Home Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>Passports submitted by the spouses of British Citizens who are applying to come to the UK are usually held at an UKVI Decision Making Centre pending a decision being made.</p><p>The passports are stored securely and returned to customers directly by courier or via a Visa Application Centre at various locations overseas once the consideration process is completed. The transfer and transit of passports between Decision Making Centres and the Visa Applications Centres is closely monitored and records of each shipment move are kept.</p><p>There is also the opportunity where UKVI can assess applications from digital images of passports. However, the physical passport is required for UKVI to affix a vignette when a decision is made.</p><p>In most locations there is an option for customers to keep their passport until a decision has been made on their application with payment of an additional fee.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-07T14:11:11.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910399/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910399/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Immigration: Married People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure the safe and timely return of passports submitted to the Home Office by spouses of British citizens wishing to come to the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Afshar",,"Baroness Afshar","HL8157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910400","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>​We have concerns about restrictions on civil and political freedoms in China, particularly around ethnic minority rights; the death penalty; and freedom of expression, association and assembly. We also remain concerned about restrictions on freedom of religion or belief. We are aware of reports of the closure or demolition of places of worship, of the removal of religious symbols, and that individuals are being harassed or detained for their beliefs across China.</p><p>The Prime Minister raised human rights when she visited China in February 2018. We raise the full range of our human rights concerns in China at the UK/China human rights dialogue, which last took place in Beijing in June 2017.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-05T16:29:35.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910400/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910400/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","China: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of human rights and religious rights in China.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL8158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910401","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>​We are aware of reports of significant numbers of individuals being detained by the Chinese authorities in re-education camps in the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region. Our Embassy in Beijing has not been able to directly verify these reports: however my officials will continue to monitor the situation in Xinjiang closely.</p><p>We remain deeply concerned about restrictions on freedom of religion or belief in China, particularly in Xinjiang. We raised our concerns with the Chinese authorities at the last UK/China Human Rights Dialogue, which took place in Beijing in June 2017. We will seek to raise them again at the next UK/China Human Rights Dialogue, which is due to take place later this year.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-05T16:30:21.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910401/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910401/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","China: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of allegations of the brainwashing of Muslims in internment programmes in China.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL8159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910402","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-11","<p>The British Government remains committed to promoting and defending freedom of religion or belief (FoRB) for individuals of all faiths or beliefs, in India and elsewhere. We shall continue to engage with Indian contacts on a range of human rights issues, including minority representatives on religious freedoms.</p><p>The British High Commission in New Delhi and our network of Deputy High Commissions maintain an assessment of the human rights situation across India and run projects promoting minority rights, as well as working with Union and State Government to build capacity and share expertise.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-11T11:57:39.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910402/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910402/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","India: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the concerns expressed by Archbishop of Delhi regarding minorities in India and the rise of extremist Hindutva supporters.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL8160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910403","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>The British Government is aware of these comments made by the Danish Minister for Immigration and Integration. The UK enjoys a close dialogue with the Danish government on Freedom of Religion or Belief (FoRB), most recently through the recent visit of Lord Ahmad to Denmark on 18 May. The protection of the right to FoRB is a priority of Her Majesty's Government's foreign policy and will continue to be so.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T11:46:34.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910403/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910403/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Denmark: Islam","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Denmark regarding integration minister Inger Stojberg's statement on Muslims fasting during the month of Ramadan.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL8161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910404","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-06","<p>We are investing in the biggest upgrade of the Midland Main Line since it was completed in 1870. This infrastructure upgrade will create capacity for up to 50% more seats in the peak into London St Pancras.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with Network Rail on the upgrade, and based on their plans and projections at this time, delivery is expected in 2020. Before then, timetables will need to continue to be implemented taking account of the available infrastructure on the Midland Main Line and the requirements of the various train operators on the route.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the May 2018 timetable development the Department for Transport worked closely with the East Midlands Trains to ensure that the timetable change continued to provide the same level and frequency of service between Sheffield and London. The Department is having a continual dialogue with East Midlands Trains to ensure that the new timetable implementation is successful and that any possible improvements are identified and implemented in a timely manner before the transformational upgrade of the Midland Main Line is complete.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-06-06T13:52:50.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910404/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910404/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-23","Railways: Sheffield","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact of recent changes to train timetables on the total journey time of trains from Sheffield to London.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL8162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910405","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is aware of reports of blockages to the flow of the Cauca River caused by landslides in the area of the Hidroituango dam project. Details are unclear, but it is up to the Colombian authorities to decide how to respond to the risk of flooding in affected areas. The British Embassy in Bogota is monitoring the situation closely.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-05T16:30:42.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910405/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910405/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Colombia: Dams","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Colombia about the flooding of the Hidroituango hydro-electric dam scheduled for 1 July, given its possible impact on access to evidence by family members of victims of war crimes who may be buried in the area.","false","Biography information for Baroness Coussins",,"Baroness Coussins","HL8163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910406","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>We condemn the killings of Luis Alberto Torres Montoya and his brother Duvián Andrés Correa Sánchez on 8 May. Both were active members of the Antioquia Ríos Vivos organisation which champions the rights of local communities.</p><p>Through our advocacy and project work the UK has supported the work of human rights defenders in Colombia. The British Ambassador in Bogota raised our concern about levels of violence against human rights defenders most recently with the Colombian Defence Minister on 11 May. We also raised these concerns during the Universal Periodic Review (UPR) of Colombia's human rights on 10 May in Geneva. During the review, Colombia also accepted UK recommendations to improve protective measures for human rights defenders.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-05T16:31:13.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910406/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910406/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Colombia: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made, or are planning to make, to the government of Colombia regarding the recent killings of two environmental human rights defenders from the Rios Vivos non-governmental organisation.","false","Biography information for Baroness Coussins",,"Baroness Coussins","HL8164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910407","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>Following the findings of the Coroner’s verdict in 2007 we were in contact with both the Australian Federal Police (AFP) and the families involved throughout the AFP’s investigation. We respect the AFP’s 2014 decision not to pursue the case following their conclusion that there was insufficient evidence to prove an offence. We are monitoring the ongoing Administrative Appeals Tribunal in Australia.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-07T13:29:06.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910407/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910407/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Portuguese Timor: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 15 May (HL7391), what assessment they have made of the conclusion of the New South Wales’ Coroner that the Balibo five were shot or deliberately stabbed; and what action, if any, they intend to take in response to this verdict.","false","Biography information for Lord Foster of Bath",,"Lord Foster of Bath","HL8165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910408","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>​The Cabinet Office, Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Home Office and Ministry of Defence as well as the security and intelligence agencies, National Crime Agency and SO15 have been fully involved in the work to consider what changes could be made to the Consolidated Guidance. The Government will seek the views of the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament on it in the context of their wider Detainee Inquiry which will be published later this year. Mr Belhaj's case was that he was detained and forcibly conveyed through a number of jurisdictions in 2004. The Consolidated Guidance was first published in 2010. On 6 July 2010 Her Majesty's Government made clear that the publication of the Consolidated Guidance was part of its work to settle the issues of the past; make clear the rules of operation for the future; and build a framework for justice that enhanced both security and liberty.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T11:47:08.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910408/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910408/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Armed Forces: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to publish revised Consolidated Guidance to Intelligence Officers and Service Personnel on the Detention and Interviewing of Detainees Overseas, and on the Passing and Receipt of Intelligence Relating to Detainees; if so, when; and whether that Guidance will reflect the circumstances of the case of Belhaj and another v Straw and others.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL8166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910409","Treasury","false","2018-06-06","<p>Internal Lloyds reports in relation to the Halifax Bank Of Scotland, Reading branch fraud should be passed to the independent Financial Conduct Authority and Lloyds Banking Group, both of which are conducting on-going investigations on this matter.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-06-06T16:03:25.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910409/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910409/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Lloyds Banking Group","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the report by Sally Masterton on alleged fraud and misrepresentation at Lloyds Banking Group; and what steps they intend to take to address the concerns raised in that report.","false","Biography information for Lord Hollick",,"Lord Hollick","HL8167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910410","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-04","<p>There are a range of factors that have contributed to the decline of hedgehogs. As set out in the 25 Year Environment Plan, we are committed to creating or restoring 500,000 hectares of wildlife-rich habitat to provide benefits for species such as the hedgehog. Agri-environment schemes such as Countryside Stewardship provide funding to restore, extend and link important habitats and boost food resources for a range of species including hedgehogs.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to support the work being done by non-governmental organisations, such as the British Hedgehog Protection Society, including the creation of hedgehog havens and campaigns encouraging local communities to work together to look out for the hedgehog and make gardens as welcoming as possible.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-06-04T16:28:09.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910410/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910410/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-23","Hedgehogs: Conservation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to reverse the decline in hedgehog numbers.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL8168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910411","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-04","<p>The UK’s Permanent Representative to the World Meteorological Organisation (WMO) is actively engaged in discussions around the WMO budget, strategic plan and governance reform, with appropriate support from the UK Hydrological Adviser. The UK will remain closely involved in the ongoing assessment of options and the development of proposals over the next 12 months, up to the World Meteorological Congress in May - June 2019, where they will be further discussed and decisions made.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-06-04T16:19:24.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910411/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910411/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-23","World Meteorological Organisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure that the UK funding of the operational hydrology and water programmes of the World Meteorological Organisation continues at present levels and is not affected by the proposed reorganisation of that agency.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL8169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910412","Home Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>In the Serious Violence Strategy, published on 9 April 2018, the Government sets out our analysis of the trends and drivers in serious violence and this includes the role that social media plays. That analysis shows that social media has created an opportunity for rivals to antagonise each other, and for those taunts to be viewed by a much larger audience for a much longer time period. This may lead to cycles of tit-for-tat violence.</p><p>We are working with social media companies and law enforcement agencies to take preventative action to address the availability of such violent gang related material available via social media.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-07T13:40:47.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910412/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910412/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Crimes of Violence: Urban Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what research they have conducted on the influence of violent media material on the behaviours of young men in large UK cities; and what steps they are taking to monitor and address it.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL8170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910413","Home Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>On 9 April 2018, the Government published a new Serious Violence Strategy to take action to address serious violence and in particular the recent increases in knife crime, gun crime and homicide. The strategy outlines an ambitious programme of over 60 commitments and actions to tackle this issue. It establishes a new balance between prevention and the rigorous law enforcement activity. The strategy will shift our approach towards steering young people away from crime in the first place and put in place measures to tackle the root causes.</p><p>In 2010 the then Government decided to scrap the identity card scheme and the associated National Identity Register because it was expensive and represented a substantial erosion of civil liberties. This Government has no plans to revisit that decision.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-07T13:40:06.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910413/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910413/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Crimes of Violence: Urban Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what control measures they are considering to monitor and curtail the movements and violent behaviour of some young men in large UK cities; and whether these measures include the introduction of identity cards.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL8171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910414","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Government is determined to prevent and reduce the levels of homelessness, and provide people with all the support they need to rebuild their lives.</p><p>Whilst we have made no specific assessment, we know the importance of taking a truly holistic approach to tackling homelessness. It is for this reason we have established a cross government taskforce, whose membership includes the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, which will develop a strategy to end rough sleeping, before looking at wider homelessness issues. We have also launched pilots of Housing First in key regions to put some of the most hard-to-reach rough sleepers in accommodation and help them recover from complex health issues, for example substance abuse and mental health difficulties.</p><p>This builds on important action the government has taken to tackle homelessness, including implementing the Homelessness Reduction Act, which means more people will get the help they need sooner, and providing over £1.2 billion to prevent and reduce homelessness and rough sleeping through to 2020.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-06-05T16:14:07.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910414/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910414/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Homelessness","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the provision by local authorities of health, social and fitness programmes connected to accommodation for homeless people; and what funding they provide to support such programmes.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL8172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910415","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Gas Safety (Installation and Use) Regulations 1998 require that anyone employed to work on domestic gas systems is competent. An individual is deemed competent following successful completion of an industry-recognised training course and an assessment of their skills.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) working with the gas industry’s Standards Setting Body has supported the implementation of the Institution of Gas Engineers and Managers (IGEM) standard IGEM/IG/1 <em>Standards of training in gas work </em>(attached)<em>.</em> IGEM/IG/1 sets out the requirements for training in gas work, and will ensure that only those engineers who have completed an approved industry recognised training course will have access to the Accredited Certification Scheme (ACS) assessment of competence. Passing such assessment, or an Office of Qualifications and Examinations Regulation (OFQUAL) regulated National Vocational Qualification (NVQ), enables an engineer to be considered as competent and apply for Gas Safe registration.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>HSE assesses standards of gas safety through published figures on gas-related incidents in Great Britain (attached). These are reportable under the Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrence Regulations (RIDDOR). This and further information can also be found in the Cross-Government Group on Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide (CO) Awareness’ annual report for 2016/2017 (attached). The Group ensures a joined-up approach across departments, the devolved administrations and other governmental bodies to improve gas safety and tackle CO risks from all fuels.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe","HL8175","2018-06-05T16:01:54.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910415/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910415/answer","HL8173 HL8175 IGEM-IG-1 Standards of training in gas work.pdf ; HL8173 HL8175 Published figures on gas-related incidents in Great Britain.xlsx ; HL8173 HL8175 Cross-Government Group on Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide (CO) Awareness annual report for 2016-2017.pdf","HL8173 HL8175 IGEM-IG-1 Standards of training in gas work.pdf ; HL8173 HL8175 Published figures on gas-related incidents in Great Britain.xlsx ; HL8173 HL8175 Cross-Government Group on Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide (CO) Awareness annual report for 2016-2017.pdf","Standards of training in gas work  ; Gas-related incidents in Great Britain  ; Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide Awareness ","Standards of training in gas work  ; Gas-related incidents in Great Britain  ; Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide Awareness ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910415/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-23","Natural Gas: Engineers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to improve the training of gas engineers.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910416","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-06","<p>The Government has not carried out such an assessment.</p><p>The Government and its agencies do however continue to raise public awareness about the risks of carbon monoxide poisoning including recognising the symptoms of exposure.</p><p>Where carbon monoxide alarms are required or recommended, Government advice is that they should comply with British Standard BS EN 50291 which sets out that alarms shall activate rapidly to high levels of carbon monoxide and within set time periods to prolonged but lower concentrations.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-06-06T16:02:08.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910416/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910416/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Carbon Monoxide: Alarms","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of public awareness of current carbon monoxide alarms only identifying acute episodes not chronic exposure.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910417","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Gas Safety (Installation and Use) Regulations 1998 require that anyone employed to work on domestic gas systems is competent. An individual is deemed competent following successful completion of an industry-recognised training course and an assessment of their skills.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) working with the gas industry’s Standards Setting Body has supported the implementation of the Institution of Gas Engineers and Managers (IGEM) standard IGEM/IG/1 <em>Standards of training in gas work </em>(attached)<em>.</em> IGEM/IG/1 sets out the requirements for training in gas work, and will ensure that only those engineers who have completed an approved industry recognised training course will have access to the Accredited Certification Scheme (ACS) assessment of competence. Passing such assessment, or an Office of Qualifications and Examinations Regulation (OFQUAL) regulated National Vocational Qualification (NVQ), enables an engineer to be considered as competent and apply for Gas Safe registration.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>HSE assesses standards of gas safety through published figures on gas-related incidents in Great Britain (attached). These are reportable under the Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrence Regulations (RIDDOR). This and further information can also be found in the Cross-Government Group on Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide (CO) Awareness’ annual report for 2016/2017 (attached). The Group ensures a joined-up approach across departments, the devolved administrations and other governmental bodies to improve gas safety and tackle CO risks from all fuels.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe","HL8173","2018-06-05T16:01:54.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910417/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910417/answer","HL8173 HL8175 IGEM-IG-1 Standards of training in gas work.pdf ; HL8173 HL8175 Published figures on gas-related incidents in Great Britain.xlsx ; HL8173 HL8175 Cross-Government Group on Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide (CO) Awareness annual report for 2016-2017.pdf","HL8173 HL8175 IGEM-IG-1 Standards of training in gas work.pdf ; HL8173 HL8175 Published figures on gas-related incidents in Great Britain.xlsx ; HL8173 HL8175 Cross-Government Group on Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide (CO) Awareness annual report for 2016-2017.pdf","Standards of training in gas work  ; Gas-related incidents in Great Britain  ; Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide Awareness ","Standards of training in gas work  ; Gas-related incidents in Great Britain  ; Gas Safety and Carbon Monoxide Awareness ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910417/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-23","Natural Gas: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the standards of gas safety in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910418","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-07","<p>The Department funds research on health and social care through the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR). The usual practice of NIHR is not to ring-fence funds for expenditure on particular topics such as dementia or the effects of exposure to indoor air pollutants such as carbon monoxide. Research proposals in all areas compete for the funding available. The NIHR welcomes funding applications for research into any aspect of human health. Applications are subject to peer review and judged in open competition, with awards made on the basis of the importance of the topic to patients and health and care services, value for money and scientific quality. In all disease areas, the amount of NIHR funding depends on the volume and quality of scientific activity.</p><p>The Department has asked the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to develop guidance on indoor air pollution in homes. NICE has worked with Public Health England to develop this scope. The focus will be on interventions related to the structure of, ventilation of, and materials used in, new/existing or retrofitted homes as well as on people’s knowledge, attitude and behaviour in relation to indoor air pollution. The guideline is to be published in September 2019.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-06-07T15:02:51.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910418/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910418/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Carbon Monoxide: Poisoning","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will commission research into the impact of exposure to chronic levels of carbon monoxide through exposure to flueless gaseous appliances such as cookers, grills, hobs and gas fires on levels of dementia in the population.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910419","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-07","<p>In both cases the councils’ proposals included well developed business cases, providing clear evidence of estimated costs and savings. The former Secretary of State considered these when concluding that these proposals fully met the criteria for implementing mergers and unitarisations as set out in my statements to the House on 26 February and 22 March. How savings are used and value for money achieved most effectively will be matters for the new councils, which are accountable to their local electorates.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-06-07T15:39:38.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910419/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910419/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Local Government: South West","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what cost-benefit analyses were done before the Somerset and Dorset local government re-organisations were agreed; and whether safeguards exist to prevent savings and value-for-money being absorbed by increase in salaries and other administrative costs.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL8177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910420","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Government is currently considering the Update Report from the Lead Ammunition Group.</p><p> </p><p>The European Chemicals Agency (ECHA) is currently carrying out a review of the potential risks presented by lead ammunition to establish if a case can be made to regulate their use within the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will consider both the Lead Ammunition Group Update Report and the findings of the ECHA review before deciding whether any changes to the current Regulations are required. The EHCA review is expected to be published in the summer.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-06-04T16:29:40.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910420/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910420/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-23","Lead: Ammunition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the Update Report from the Lead Ammunition Group, published in April, into harmful effects of lead shot on humans and animals.","false","Biography information for Lord Krebs",,"Lord Krebs","HL8178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910421","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-05","<p>Through the Environmental Protection (Restriction on Use of Lead Shot) (England) Regulations 1999, the use of lead shot ammunition is restricted to protect waterfowl from lead poisoning. Its use is banned on all foreshores, certain Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) and for the shooting of all ducks and geese, coot and moorhen. The supply of lead weights for fishing is also prohibited.</p><p> </p><p>Natural England is fully compliant with these regulations on the land which it manages. The Forestry Commission voluntarily decided to use non-lead alternatives on the public forest estate for the control of deer and wild boar. From November 2016 onwards all the venison processed through Forest Enterprise England (FEE) larders will have been culled with non-lead ammunition.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-06-05T16:06:18.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910421/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910421/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-23","Lead: Ammunition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they will take to reduce the poisoning of humans and animals through ingesting lead ammunition deposited by public bodies or third parties acting under contract or licence from public bodies.","false","Biography information for Lord Krebs",,"Lord Krebs","HL8179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910422","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>All applications for discretionary leave made by victims of modern slavery are considered on a case by case basis and processing times vary with complexity of individual circumstance.</p><p>The Home Office does not publish data on the processing times for such applications. As part of the ongoing reform of the National Referral Mechanism, changes will be made to ensure a quicker, more certain decision making process that victims have confidence in and which may include customer service standards.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL8181 ; HL8182","2018-06-05T11:48:36.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910422/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910422/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, in each of the last five calendar years, what percentage of victims of modern slavery who have made an application for discretionary leave to remain following a positive National Referral Mechanism conclusive grounds decision (excluding those non-EEA national victims who were considered for discretionary leave on the grounds of their personal circumstances automatically) have received a decision about the discretionary leave within (1) 45 days, (2) eight weeks, and (3) six months.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL8180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910423","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>All applications for discretionary leave made by victims of modern slavery are considered on a case by case basis and processing times vary with complexity of individual circumstance.</p><p>The Home Office does not publish data on the processing times for such applications. As part of the ongoing reform of the National Referral Mechanism, changes will be made to ensure a quicker, more certain decision making process that victims have confidence in and which may include customer service standards.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL8180 ; HL8182","2018-06-05T11:48:36.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910423/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910423/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the average length of time for a victim of modern slavery to wait for a decision following an application for discretionary leave to remain in the calendar years 2016 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL8181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910424","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>All applications for discretionary leave made by victims of modern slavery are considered on a case by case basis and processing times vary with complexity of individual circumstance.</p><p>The Home Office does not publish data on the processing times for such applications. As part of the ongoing reform of the National Referral Mechanism, changes will be made to ensure a quicker, more certain decision making process that victims have confidence in and which may include customer service standards.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL8180 ; HL8181","2018-06-05T11:48:36.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910424/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910424/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the customer service standard target time for making a decision on an application for discretionary leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL8182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910425","Home Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>The Government’s Response to the House of Lords Select Committee on the Licensing Act 2003 made a commitment to issue a call for evidence on the Committee’s recommendation to revoke these orders.</p><p>The call for evidence will be issued shortly.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-07T13:57:36.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910425/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910425/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Licensing Laws: Airports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they intend to revoke the orders which prevent the Licensing Act 2003 from applying to airport bars airside.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL8183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910426","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-05","<p>I refer the Noble Baroness to the written response I gave to question HL 6504 on 12 April 2018.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-06-05T16:09:33.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910426/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910426/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-23","Fisheries: Quotas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress has been made on sharing unused cod and other fisheries quotas with inshore fishermen.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL8184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910427","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>We welcome the important contribution that voluntary, charitable and non-governmental organisations make to the UK asylum system and believe the best way to support those who have been refused asylum and who have no lawful basis to remain in the UK is in helping them to leave the UK voluntarily and reintegrate into their communities in their country of origin.</p><p>The Home Office does not fund or take action against churches or other places of worship that offer support to failed asylum seekers.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL8188","2018-06-05T11:47:29.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910427/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910427/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Asylum: Religious Buildings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what support they are giving to places of worship that provide sanctuary for asylum seekers regardless of their immigration status.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL8185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910428","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Croydon Premium Service Centre does not deal with any Asylum cases.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-05T11:48:57.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910428/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910428/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Asylum: Croydon","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many asylum interviews were held at the Croydon premium service centre in each of the last six months.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL8186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910429","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>In the period requested, there were no prosecutions for those assisting asylum seekers whose claims had failed.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-05T11:52:59.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910429/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910429/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many people were prosecuted in (1) 2016, and (2) 2017, for assisting asylum seekers whose claims had failed.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL8187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910430","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>We welcome the important contribution that voluntary, charitable and non-governmental organisations make to the UK asylum system and believe the best way to support those who have been refused asylum and who have no lawful basis to remain in the UK is in helping them to leave the UK voluntarily and reintegrate into their communities in their country of origin.</p><p>The Home Office does not fund or take action against churches or other places of worship that offer support to failed asylum seekers.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL8185","2018-06-05T11:47:29.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910430/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910430/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action, if any, they have taken against churches or other organisations for supporting failed asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL8188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910431","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Home Office publishes data on the number of asylum cases pending a decision at the end of each quarter in table as_01_q (asylum, volume 1) of the quarterly <em>Immigration Statistics</em> release.</p><p>The latest figures show the total number of asylum cases pending a decision at the end of March 2018 was 24,593. Of this total, the number pending an initial decision was 22,100. The data can be found at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/709299/asylum1-mar-2018-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/709299/asylum1-mar-2018-tables.ods</a></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-05T11:52:42.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910431/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910431/answer","Asylum 1-Mar 2018 tables.xlsx","Asylum 1-Mar 2018 tables.xlsx","Tables as_o1_q - Asylum vol 1 ","Tables as_o1_q - Asylum vol 1 ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910431/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many asylum claims are currently waiting to be processed.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL8189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910432","Home Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>Other than in certified cases, the Home Office does not intentionally remove individuals whose claim for protection is still being processed.The Home Office does not routinely publish statistics on the number of individuals wrongfully removed or deported, or keep central records of people who have been wrongfully removed or deported.</p><p>However, as was noted in a letter provided to the Home Affairs Select Committee on 14 May 2018, the department identified 17 cases since 2015 in which a person was returned to the UK after being removed,</p><p>i. in five cases, the Department or the Court found no legal basis for their remaining here; the Department has subsequently removed or is seeking to remove that person again from the UK;</p><p>ii. in nine cases, proceedings are ongoing; and</p><p>iii. in three cases, the Department or the Court has found those people to have a legal basis to remain in the UK. (It is not necessarily the case that the legal reason which led to those people being brought back to the UK is the same grounds on which they have acquired a legal basis to remain).</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-06T16:50:36.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910432/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910432/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many asylum seekers were removed from the UK while their applications were still being processed in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL8190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910433","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>We are concerned by reports of these arrests and are monitoring closely. The Foreign Secretary has raised our concerns with the Saudi authorities.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T11:59:01.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910433/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910433/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Saudi Arabia: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Saudi Arabia following the arrests of women's rights activists in connection with the decision to allow Saudi women to drive.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Sandwich",,"The Earl of Sandwich","HL8191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910434","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>We understand both the Ministry of Interior Ombudsman and the National Institute for Human Rights have been active and responsive to the issues raised by the family.</p><p>We continue to monitor the cases of family members of Mr Alwadaei and have raised them at a senior level with the Government of Bahrain.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T11:59:22.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910434/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910434/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Sayed Alwadaei","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 22 May (HL7774), whether the investigations by the oversight bodies in Bahrain into the torture allegations of Sayed Alwadaei’s family members were swift and thorough.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910435","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>​We understand the investigation into the deaths of protesters during the security operation to clear an illegal gathering in Diraz is ongoing. We will continue to monitor events in Bahrain closely. Should we have concerns we will raise them at an appropriately senior level with the Government of Bahrain.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-07T13:29:35.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910435/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910435/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Bahrain: Protest","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 31 July 2017 (HL930), what representations they have made to the government of Bahrain regarding the investigation into the killing of five protesters in Duraz on 23 May 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910436","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>The UK has concerns about the revocation of nationality when it renders individuals stateless. We have raised this issue at a senior level with the Government of Bahrain.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T13:15:30.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910436/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910436/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Bahrain: Nationality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of citizenship revocations in Bahrain; and what representations they have made to the government of Bahrain about them.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910437","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>We welcome the investigation and recommendation of the Special Investigations Unit and the subsequent decision of the Minister of Justice to refer the cases of Mohamed Ramadan and Husain Moosa back to the Court of Cassation for retrial. The recommendation and subsequent decision has been made available in the public domain. We will continue to closely monitor these cases.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T13:16:23.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910437/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910437/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Bahrain: Torture","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 3 April (HL6557), on what basis they consider the Bahraini Special Investigation Unit’s investigation into the death-row inmates Mohamed Ramadan and Husain Moosa to be transparent.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910438","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has funded programmes to support building effective and accountable public and judicial institutions in Bahrain. All of our work fully complies with our domestic and international human rights obligations and Her Majesty's Government standards of assurance and accountability to ensure value for money for UK taxpayers. In financial year 2016-17, £1.52 million was spent on UK expertise to Bahraini-led reform through the Conflict Stability and Security Fund. No funding was received from the Integrated Activity Fund in 2016-17.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T13:17:00.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910438/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910438/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Bahrain: Technical Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the allocated budget for Bahrain from the Integrated Activity Fund in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910439","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-07","<p>In the period 1 January 2015 to 31 December 2017, there was one prosecution (in 2016) under the Female Genital Mutilation Act 2003, and that did not result in a conviction. This data relates only to those proceedings where the principal offence prosecuted was under the Female Genital Mutilation Act 2003.</p><p> </p><p>Where a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences, data would only record the offence for which the heaviest penalty was imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected would be the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty was the most severe.</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2018 will be published in May 2019.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-06-07T15:40:15.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910439/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910439/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-23","Female Genital Mutilation: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many prosecutions there have been under the Female Genital Mutilation Act 2003 in each year since 2015; and how many have been successful.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL8197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910440","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-08","<p>Following their introduction in July 2015, there have been 222 applications and 205 orders made for Female Genital Mutilation Protection Orders, up to 31 December 2017.</p><p> </p><p>In this period no breaches of an FGM Protection order have been dealt with in the criminal courts. In the Family Courts, proceedings for breach would be dealt with as a contempt of court matter and are not recorded separately. The information could therefore only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on FGM Protection Orders are publicly available as part of the Family Courts Statistics Quarterly series at https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/family-court-statistics-quarterly. The next publication of Family Court Statistics Quarterly is due on 28 June 2018. This will provide data up to the end of March 2018.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL8199","2018-06-08T10:44:55.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910440/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910440/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-23","Female Genital Mutilation Protection Orders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many Female Genital Mutilation Orders have been (1) sought, and (2) issued, since they were introduced under the Serious Crime Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL8198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910441","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-08","<p>Following their introduction in July 2015, there have been 222 applications and 205 orders made for Female Genital Mutilation Protection Orders, up to 31 December 2017.</p><p> </p><p>In this period no breaches of an FGM Protection order have been dealt with in the criminal courts. In the Family Courts, proceedings for breach would be dealt with as a contempt of court matter and are not recorded separately. The information could therefore only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on FGM Protection Orders are publicly available as part of the Family Courts Statistics Quarterly series at https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/family-court-statistics-quarterly. The next publication of Family Court Statistics Quarterly is due on 28 June 2018. This will provide data up to the end of March 2018.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL8198","2018-06-08T10:44:55.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910441/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910441/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-23","Female Genital Mutilation Protection Orders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether any Female Genital Mutilation Protection Orders have been breached in each year since 2015; and, in each case, whether they were dealt with (1) by criminal prosecution, or (2) in the Family Court.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL8199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910442","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-05","<p>Section 6 of the Health and safety at Work etc. Act 1974 places duties on any person who designs, manufacturers, imports or supplies any article for use at work to ensure that it will be safe and without risks to health, which applies to artificial intelligence and machine learning software. Section 6(1)(b) requires such testing and examination as may be necessary to ensure that any article for use at work is safe and without risks but does not specify specific testing regimes. It is for the designer, manufacturer, importer or supplier to develop tests that are sufficient to demonstrate that their product is safe.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Safety Executive's (HSE) Foresight Centre monitors developments in artificial intelligence to identify potential health and safety implications for the workplace over the next decade. The Centre reports that there are likely to be increasing numbers of automated systems in the workplace, including robots and artificial intelligence. HSE will continue to monitor the technology as it develops and will respond appropriately on the basis of risk.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2018-06-05T16:03:44.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910442/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910442/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-23","Industrial Health and Safety: Artificial Intelligence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the extent to which section 6 of the Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974 applies to artificial intelligence or machine learning software that is used in the workplace to (1) control or animate physical things in the workplace, (2) design articles for use in the workplace, or (3) support human decision-making processes running on computers under the control of the employer with an impact on people's health and safety; and whether, in each case, testing regimes exist as set out in section 6(1)(b) of that Act.","false","Biography information for Lord Stevenson of Balmacara",,"Lord Stevenson of Balmacara","HL8200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910443","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Home Office Homicide Index holds data on the number of people in England and Wales who have been killed by persons who have been previously convicted of homicide. The information is given in the table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="11"><p><strong>Table 1: Number of homicides in England and Wales known to have been committed by suspects who had been previously convicted of homicide<sup>1,2,3</sup> , 2007/08 to 2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England and Wales</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2007/08</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008/09</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of homicide victims</strong></p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>1. Source: Homicide Index, Home Office </em></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>2. Homicide Index data are designated as National Statistics</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="11"><p>3. As at 16 November 2017; figures are subject to revision as cases are dealt with by the police and by the courts, or as further information becomes available.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>The figure excludes persons who have been killed by those who may have been convicted outside England and Wales (for whom there is incomplete information), and persons who have been killed by those not previously convicted of homicide by reason of their mental state.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-06-05T12:01:25.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910443/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910443/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Homicide: Reoffenders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 26 July 2017, how many people were killed by individuals who had previously been convicted of murder or manslaughter, in each of the last ten years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL8201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910444","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>​We abstained on calls for a Commission of Inquiry into recent violence in Gaza because the substance of the resolution was not impartial and balanced. We could not support an investigation that refused to explicitly examine the action of non-state actors such as Hamas. An investigation of this kind would not provide us with a comprehensive assessment of accountability. However, the UK continues to fully support the need for an independent and transparent investigation into recent events. We call directly on Israel to carry out a transparent inquiry into the Israeli Defense Forces' conduct at the border fence and to demonstrate how this will achieve a sufficient level of independence. We believe this investigation should include international members. We urge that the findings of such an investigation be made public and if, wrongdoing is found, that those responsible are held to account. The Foreign Secretary stressed the importance of Israel conducting an independent investigation when he spoke to Prime Minister Netanyahu on 16 May.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T13:52:08.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910444/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910444/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Gaza: Israel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government for what reasons they abstained from voting on the resolution of the United Nations Human Rights Council held on 18 May, calling for an independent investigation into recent violence in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL8202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910445","Department for International Trade","false","2018-06-07","<p>Sales of military items to other countries by UK companies require export licences. Export licence applications are rigorously assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all prevailing circumstances at the time of the application. The Government will not issue a licence if to do so would be inconsistent with these Criteria.</p><p>The Government is monitoring the situation in Israel and Gaza very closely and will revoke extant export licences if they are assessed to be no longer consistent with licensing criteria.</p><p>The policy framework for assessing exports of military items was announced to Parliament by the former Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, the Rt. Hon Member for Twickenham, Sir Vince Cable, as a Written Ministerial Statement on 25 March 2014.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-06-07T13:39:24.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910445/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910445/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-23","Arms Trade: Israel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will review their policy on arms sales to Israel, given the recent violence in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL8203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910446","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>The UK is concerned about the high number of deaths and casualties during protests in Gaza, including the volume of live fire used. The Foreign Secretary, the Minister for the Middle East and North Africa and I have all raised the use of force with Israeli authorities. The Foreign Secretary spoke to both Prime Minister Netanyahu and President Abbas on 16 May, where he encouraged them to call for calm and work to de-escalate the situation. There is an urgent need to establish the facts; the UK continues to fully support the need for an independent and transparent investigation into recent events. We call directly on Israel to carry out a transparent inquiry into the Israeli Defense Forces' conduct at the border fence and to demonstrate how this will achieve a sufficient level of independence.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-06-06T14:30:10.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910446/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910446/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","Gaza: Israel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the United Nations Human Rights Council’s resolution of 18 May that the use of force by Israel in Gaza was disproportionate and indiscriminate.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL8204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909257","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-24","<p>Last December the Department launched a consultation on ‘Proposals for the creation of a Major Road Network’ which closed on 19th March.</p><p> </p><p>A formal consultation response will be published during summer 2018 prior to the expected launch of the Major Road Network (MRN) programme before the end of the year.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-24T10:09:57.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909257/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909257/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-22","Roads","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress the Government has made on the establishment of the Major Road Network.","false","Biography information for Mr Simon Clarke","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Mr Simon Clarke","905542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909261","Treasury","false","2018-05-22","<p>People’s disposable income is now 4.6% higher in real terms than in 2010. That is because we have turned around the economy and held taxes down.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-22T13:37:42.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909261/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909261/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-22","Cost of Living","1","House of Commons","What progress the Government has made on supporting families with the cost of living.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","905491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909270","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Government’s Industrial Strategy has set out a long-term approach to boost the UK’s productivity growth and ensure that we’re building an economy fit for the future. Our White Paper has set out a range of measures aimed at increasing investment from the private and public sector and includes a commitment to increase total R&amp;D investment to 2.4% of GDP by 2027. The Government will support UK priorities in key areas of innovation through investing in the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund, with over £1.7bn committed so far through the first two waves. One example is the £246m Faraday Battery Challenge to position the UK to be at the cutting edge of battery technology. We have also just held an open Expressions of Interest process for potential programmes for a third wave of the Challenge Fund.</p><p> </p><p>As we leave the EU we remain committed to making the UK the best place in Europe to own and grow a business. The Department for International Trade (DIT) and the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) have dedicated teams who promote the UK as a destination for investment into manufacturing and to boost trade from UK manufacturing companies abroad. In 2016/17, on marine, for example, the DIT High Value Campaign programme secured around £214 million of UK Exports; the Aerospace team supported over £7 billion of aerospace exports; and the DIT rail team recorded overseas export wins to the value of £323million, including manufactured goods.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-06-04T14:47:56.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909270/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909270/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-22","Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support British manufacturing firms to diversify into new (a) consumer and (b) overseas markets.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","146701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909271","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-04","<p>The development of ABLE is a commercial matter for the company.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-06-04T14:45:56.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909271/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909271/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-22","ABLE Humber Port","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support the development of the Able Marine Energy Park.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","146924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909272","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-06","<p>There are already furs that cannot be imported onto the UK, including cat and dog fur and products, and seal skins and products from commercial hunts.</p><p>The Treaty on the Functioning of the EU (TFEU) places restrictions on the introduction of measures that impair the free movement of goods within the EU market.</p><p>Where there are EU harmonising measures relevant to the movement of fur – including the Animal By-Products Regulation in respect of untreated fur and the Seal Products Regulation – any derogation from those in the form of a national restriction would need to meet the requirements of Article 114 TFEU or any specific safeguard measure included in the harmonising legislation. This would involve notifying the measures to the European Commission who would need to be satisfied that the issue is “specific to that Member State”, that it would not amount to a means of arbitrary discrimination or a disguised restriction on trade, or an obstacle to the functioning of the internal market.</p><p>Introducing a ban in the absence of such consent where it is needed would breach Article 114 TFEU.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-06T14:06:30.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909272/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909272/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-22","Furs: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if the Government will take steps to reduce the level of fur imported from overseas.","false","Biography information for Wera Hobhouse","Bath","Wera Hobhouse","146954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909273","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-04","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the answer given to PQ 143186 on 15th May.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-06-04T13:41:16.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909273/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909273/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-22","Holidays","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government taking to ensure that people (a) in and (b) out work has the opportunity to have a holiday each year regardless of their income or personal circumstances.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","146878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909274","Scotland Office","false","2018-05-31","<p>I regularly meet with representatives from across the tourism sector and would be happy to meet VisitScotland to discuss this important issue.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-05-31T14:32:26.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909274/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909274/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-05-22","Holidays: Low Incomes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will meet representatives of VisitScotland to discuss (a) its ScotSpirit scheme's provision of holidays to low income families and (b) the positive effect that holidays can have on family life.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","146879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909275","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-31","<p>Nigeria is a secular, multi-ethnic and multi-religious country. We are aware of concerns that in some cases prosecutions have not been secured for some religion-related crimes and that a full assessment of the effectiveness of prosecution in such cases might not have been made. We urge the Nigerian government to investigate fully all such crimes and hold those responsible to account. We continue to support Nigerian authorities' efforts to strengthen their criminal justice system and ensure accountability.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-05-31T09:58:56.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909275/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909275/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-22","Nigeria: Religious Hatred","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what is his assessment he has made of the effectiveness of prosecution of religion-related crimes in Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","146852"
