"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909386","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-04","<p>Ministers and officials regularly have discussions with many local authorities about a wide range of issues, which may include reorganisation from a two tier structure to unitary status.</p><p>In particular there have been discussions with councils in Buckinghamshire, Dorset and Oxfordshire, where proposals for unitarisation have been submitted, and with councils in Northamptonshire which have been invited to make unitary proposals.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-06-04T11:18:16.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909386/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909386/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-22","Unitary Councils: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many and which local authorities are engaged in discussions with his Department on reorganisation from a two-tier structure to unitary status.","false","Biography information for Gareth Snell","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Gareth Snell","146952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909387","Department for International Trade","false","2018-06-04","<p>I refer the Hon. Member for Sheffield Central to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Birmingham, Hall Green on 26 April 2018, UIN: 137004 and the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Newcastle upon Tyne North on 3 May 2018, UIN: 139483.</p><p>Details of the meetings held by the Department for International Trade (DIT) Ministers are published on the Gov.uk website and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-international-trade&amp;publication_type=transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-international-trade&amp;publication_type=transparency-data</a></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-06-04T15:50:56.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909387/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909387/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-22","Legatum Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what meetings (a) he, (b) Ministers in his Department, (c) advisers in his Department and (d) officials in his Department have held with representatives of the Legatum Institute since July 2016; and what the topics for discussion were at those meetings.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","146844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909388","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-06-04","<p>The service requirements are part of an ongoing commercial process and cannot be published at this time. Releasable elements of the requirements are published in the contract documentation which Government procurement transparency rules require to be published following a contract award. These rules would apply to any future contract award in relation to the Defence Fire and Rescue Project.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-06-04T15:56:40.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909388/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909388/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-22","Defence Fire and Rescue Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will publish the service specifications included in the proposed contract for the Defence Fire and Rescue Project.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","146934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909389","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>On 9 April 2018, the Government published the Serious Violence Strategy to set out the action it is taking to address serious violence, and in particular the recent increases in knife crime, gun crime and homicide.</p><p>We have reviewed the evidence and the strategy sets out the trends and drivers of serious violence. The evidence shows that homicide, knife crime and gun crime have increased since 2014 across virtually all police force areas in England and Wales, including the West Midlands. The increases have been accompanied by a shift towards younger victims and perpetrators. The analysis in the Serious Violence Strategy shows that changes in the drugs market is a major factor in the recent increases.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-05T13:59:36.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909389/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909389/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-22","Crimes of Violence: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the level of violent crime in the West Midlands; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","146846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909390","Home Office","false","2018-06-04","<p>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_Office" target="_blank">Home Office</a> collects information from police forces on the number of police recorded offences that have been committed (in full or in part) online. These data will mostly comprise cyber-enabled offences. The latest data for England and Wales for the year to December 2017 are published at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesexperimentaltables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesexperimentaltables</a> (Table E4)</p><p>These are experimental statistics and are only published at national (England and Wales) level while the Home Office works with forces to improve the data quality.</p><p>The Home Office collects additional police data on fraud and cybercrime via the National Fraud Intelligence Bureau (NFIB). These data include both cyber-dependent and cyber-enabled offences. The latest data for England and Wales for the year to December 2017 are published at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables</a> (Table A5)</p><p>Breakdowns of these data by both police force area and offence type are not held at the Home Office.</p><p>The cyber threats we face continue to grow in scale and sophistication. This is why the National Cyber Security Strategy 2016-2021 is supported by £1.9billion of transformational investment. We are continuing to invest in cyber capabilities within law enforcement at the national, regional and local levels, to ensure that law enforcement have the capabilities in place to go after the most sophisticated criminals. In particular, we will be supporting the national policing initiative to ensure that that every police force has a specialist Cyber Crime Unit. It is crucial that at the local level we provide an effective law enforcement response, support victims and give targeted prevention messages.</p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2018-06-04T15:37:32.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909390/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909390/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-22","Cybercrime: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether he has made an assessment of trends in the level of cyber crime in the West Midlands; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","146847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909391","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-30","<p>No decision has been reached on the Defence Fire and Rescue Project but the ability to provide internationally deployable fire and rescue services will be part of any outcome from the project.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-05-30T13:54:42.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909391/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909391/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-22","Defence Fire and Rescue Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans have been made under the Defence Fire and Rescue Project to ensure the Defence Fire and Rescue Service has the ability to deploy internationally.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","146935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909392","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>It is for Police and Crime Commissioners, with their Chief Constables, to consider hate crime trends for their local areas.</p><p>In England and Wales, the most recently published statistics on police recorded hate crime, for 2016/17, showed that there were 80,393 offences recorded by the police in which one or more hate crime strands were deemed to be a motivating factor. This was an increase of 29% compared with the 62,518 hate crimes recorded in 2015/16.</p><p>The 29% increase is thought to reflect both a genuine rise in hate crime around the time of the EU Referendum and Westminster Bridge terrorist attack alongside improved identification of hate crime by the police, willingness of victims to come forward and an overall improvement in how police now record crime.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-05T14:15:24.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909392/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909392/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-22","Hate Crime: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the 12 per cent rise in recorded hate crimes in the West Midlands in the last year, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","146848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909393","Treasury","false","2018-05-25","<p>The Defence Fire and Rescue Project aims to identify whether an industry service provider will provide increased value for money in the delivery of a worldwide Defence Fire and Rescue Service. A decision on the outcome of this project will be announced in due course.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-25T14:33:20.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909393/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909393/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-22","Defence Fire and Rescue Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the Treasury Approval note relating to the Defence Fire and Rescue project.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","146936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909394","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-31","<p>I welcome the positive report by the Appellate Body in the dispute brought by the US on support to Airbus. It confirms that the EU has not provided any prohibited subsidies and has taken the necessary action regarding the bulk of the findings in the original WTO case. Nevertheless, a small number of issues remain for the EU to deal with. We take our international commitments seriously and we are acting swiftly to make sure that we are in line with WTO rules. We now look forward to the WTO report into the US efforts to bring themselves into line with WTO requirements, following previous rulings that confirmed continuing massive US government support to Boeing</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-05-31T09:36:44.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909394/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909394/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-22","Airbus: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the World Trade Organization 15 May 2018 ruling that the European Union failed to comply with requests to end subsidies for Airbus.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","146775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909395","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-31","<p>Information provided in export licence applications (such as names of exporters, end users and third parties) is confidential. However, the Government publishes Official Statistics about export licences on a quarterly and annual basis, which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data</a>.</p><p>These reports contain detailed information on export licences issued, refused or revoked, by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences.</p><p>Currently these reports contain information up to 31 December 2017. Information covering 1 January to 31 March will be published in July 2018.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","146773 ; 146774","2018-05-31T15:19:53.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909395/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909395/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-22","Standard Individual Export Licences: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 14 May 2018 to Question 142370 on Iran: Standard Individual Export Licences, how many applications submitted by (a) Jeppesen UK, (b) CDG, (c) Aviall, (d) Tapestry Solutions and (e) AerData for licences to export goods to Iran have been received by the Export Control Organisation since the implementation of the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action on 16 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","146776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909396","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>Analysis of the data on the number of women affected was completed by the end of May. My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has provided this information in a Written Ministerial Statement, <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-06-04/HCWS731/" target="_blank">HCWS731</a>, published today.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-04T15:56:35.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909396/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909396/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-22","Breast Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the Oral Statement of 2 May 2018 on Breast Cancer Screening, Official Report, column 315, what estimate his Department has made of the number of women in Wolverhampton who were not sent an invitation to a final routine breast cancer screening as a result of the computer algorithm failure.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","146849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909397","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-04","<p>PIP assessments are completed by third-party providers rather than the Department itself. We do not rate assessments but we do independently audit assessment reports to ensure that the advice provided to the Department’s Case Managers is of suitable quality, fully explained and justified.</p><p> </p><p>PIP Assessment Provider performance by audit grading can be accessed using the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/work-and-pensions-select-committee-pip-and-esa-assessments-inquiry-supporting-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/work-and-pensions-select-committee-pip-and-esa-assessments-inquiry-supporting-statistics</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-06-04T16:45:07.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909397/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909397/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-22","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of personal independence payment assessments carried out by (a) her Department and (b) other assessors that were rated as (i) acceptable, (b) acceptable with amendments, (c) acceptable with feedback, and (d) unacceptable in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","146760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909398","Department for Education","false","2018-06-04","<p>Disabled Student Allowance (DSA) is available solely where a student is obliged to incur additional costs while studying as a result of their disability. In the case of computer equipment, it was clear from evidence that this had become a mainstream cost for all students and that disabled students should therefore contribute towards the cost of computer equipment recommended through DSA. On receipt of a DSA Needs Assessment Report, the Student Loans Company will make a decision where necessary as to whether a particular piece of equipment that has been recommended is a mainstream cost or not.</p><p> </p><p>Maintenance loans are available to help fund the costs of study that all students incur. However, the department does not issue guidance to students on how they should spend these funds.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-06-04T16:00:17.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909398/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909398/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-22","Disabled Students' Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 26 April 2018 to Question 137102 on Disabled Students' Allowances, excluding the cost of a standard computer, what other equipment his Department includes as a mainstream cost to participate in Higher Education; and what items are covered by a maintenance loan.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","146720"
