"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909511","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-25","<p>The national commitment for the dementia diagnosis rate is two-thirds of the estimated population living with dementia to have a formal diagnosis. At the end of April 2018, 116 of 195 clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) had met the two-thirds national standard.</p><p> </p><p>A national diagnosis rate of at least 66.7% was initially achieved at the end 2015, and this has been maintained ever since. The current national dementia diagnosis rate is 67.3% (April 2018).</p><p> </p><p>NHS England recognises that CCGs have varying levels of need for support based on their performance against the indicators, and has developed a support offer to assist areas in improving dementia services including diagnosis rates.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","146970","2018-05-25T13:52:13.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909511/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909511/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-22","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many Care Commissioning Groups (CCGs) have reached a 75 per cent formal diagnosis rate for dementia; and what support his Department plans to provide CCGs that have not reached that target.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","146969"
